passages.text: - 2025 has been a mixed one for our survey. The index pulled back throughout May, as softness in many urban markets, built on rural and suburban weakness, to weigh on the index. After steadily moving higher in late May and early June, the index has pulled back in July and August, on some softness in suburban, rural & urban markets.- Commission rates continue to pull back – pages 3-4.- Current revenue generated per transaction & source of that revenue – page 5- Share of unrepresented buyers has moved higher post NAR settlement – page 6- Current inventory levels & rate level needed before demand improves – pages 7-8- Share of contracts failing to close & buyers or sellers market? – pages 9-10- How difficult is it to secure financing? – page 11
Evercore ISI House Price Survey Y/Y% Aug 21 2.9%

The Evercore ISI House Price Survey was first released in August of 2002, we have spoken weekly to over 40 residential real- estate agents across 23 states asking them the following question. What is the Y/Y percentage change of house prices in your region? The purpose of the survey is to track the change in house prices on a timely basis, and by speaking with our contacts on a weekly basis we can keep a pulse on the industry and release data ahead of the govt.

In order to get a better understanding of the current state of real-estate commissions, so we can gage the impact of the NAR settlement, in late July 2024 we began asking survey participants about their most recent and historic commission rates. On average, the most recent commission for a buyers agent was 2.5%, and for a listing agent it was 2.7%, both down from their historic average of 2.8% and 3.1% respectfully.

historically, according to our participants, the vast majority of commissions, on both sides of a. esidential transaction was between \(2.5\%\) and \(3.49\%\) . With \(90\%\) of Buyers Agents and \(77\%\) isting agents reporting their historic commission rate in this range. It should be noted that espondents feel there has been some downward pressure on commissions rates for the past. ew years, a trend that accelerated in 2024. It appears some stabilization has occurred on. ommission rates for listing agents in 1H 2025, while the downward pressure continues for uyers agent commissions. Beginning last Summer, we have asked survey participants to give us a sense of how, adjusted for sales price, total revenue (including commissions, fees, bonuses etc.) is currently compared to their historic normal. On average \(70\%\) of respondents mentioned that it is "about normal", up from \(64\%\) in late 2024, but down from \(79\%\) when we first asked last August.

All of our survey respondents currently receive revenue from commission, as a smaller portion of individuals, many who are more involved in rentals, receive revenue through various fees for service. Keep an eye on as we move through 2025 to see if the NAR settlement has an impact and there is a continued shift toward other revenue streams.

We asked respondents to gage the share of buyers who are currently unrepresented. In the first few days post Aug \(17^{\text{th}}\) 2024 the numbers were little changed as, on average, \(28\%\) of buyers were showing up unrepresented in late August, similar to what survey participants report is their historic norm. However, a change has since occurred over as respondents report on average \(35\%\) of buyers are now showing up unrepresented.

Inventory levels continue to remain a headwind for many participants, though less so then they were earlier this year, as \(44\%\) of respondents, down from \(78\%\) last check, report current inventory levels in their market are lower than normal, while \(34\%\) , up from \(14\%\) in early 2025, report higher than normal inventory levels. Broken out by type of market, inventory levels have improved in urban, suburban and rural markets.

Currently \(40\%\) of participants report the share of contracts that are falling through and not ending in a sale is larger than normal, down from a record high of \(49\%\) last check. While \(8\%\) of respondents, up from a record low of \(2\%\) in our Feb. check, report a smaller than normal share of contracts falling through.
Relative To Normal, The Share Of Contracts That Are Falling Through And Not Ending In A Sale Is ...
Relative To Normal, What Share Of Contracts Are Falling Through And Not Ending In A Sale?

When asked if the current market favors buyers or sellers, \(44\%\) of respondents believe sellers have the upper hand when it comes to trading new homes, up from \(37\%\) in December but below \(53\%\) from one year ago, while \(39\%\) say the market for existing homes is a sellers market, down from \(63\%\) last Summer, and \(25\%\) believe sellers have the upper hand when it comes to trading investment / vacation properties, down from \(44\%\) last June.

It should also be noted that currently \(18\%\) of respondents, down from \(30\%\) in June of 2024, mentioned that they are seeing a higher- than- normal level of contingences being waved, with participants citing financing and inspection contingencies as the two most likely to be waived.

Homebuilders and residential real estate agents in our surveys tell us mortgage availability remains better than normal (normal=5.0), in our quarterly survey, and we saw an uptick in buyers' ease in getting mortgage financing for both FHA and Non- FHA loans.
